 Farming-based Money flow 30 (2004) 195-202 
 
 The adoption of intensive monocrop (the study of plants) 
 in southern Cameroon 
 James Gockowski a,a-- , Michel Ndoumbe b 
 a 
 
 IITA-Cameroon, c/o L.W. Lambourn &amp; Co., Carolyn House, 26 Dingwall Road, Croydon CR9 3EE, UK 
 b Institut de Interesting Agricole pour le Developpement, P.O. Box 2067, IRAD, Yaounde, Cameroon 
 Received 27 February 2001; received in changed form 16 August 2002; accepted 6 November 2002 
 
 Abstract 
 Results from a 1997 survey of 208 families in the humid forest zone of southern Cameroon point to/show that African policy 
 makers trying to strengthen farming-based production should focus attention on the (plant-related) sub-part/area. The survey, which 
 gathered information on (plant-related) production practices, found that the average expense on agro-chemical inputs by 
 (plant-related) producers using monocrop production systems was 190 US$/ha, which greatly goes beyond the FAO reported national average expense of 6.50 US$/ha. A logit model of monocrop adoption pointed to/showed that the size of land holding per 
 household had a negative effect on adoption, matching with population-driven technical change and that increases in unit 
 transportation costs significantly decreased the chance of adoption. These studies suggest that policy makers should 
 target (plant-related) (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) in areas of higher population density and (help increase/show in a good way) investment in (away from cities) roads. The age of 
 the household head had a significant negative and elastic effect on adoption, which in combination with an increase in the 
 group of younger farmers in the (away from cities) population caused by macro-money-based events added/gave to the spread of stronger 
 (the study of plants). In the study area, roughly two-thirds of (away from cities) families also produce cocoa and the amount of cocoa produced 
 was positively connected with adoption of intensive (plant-related) systems suggesting that export crop promotion indirectly 
 helped (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) of farming. Women's participation in intensive monocrop production was limited and efforts to 
 (help increase/show in a good way) their greater involvement are recommended. 
