 Low levels of farming-based (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) have 
 been linked to the non-suitability of farming-based 
 lands, inappropriate farming-based policies, (not existing at all) 
 agro-chemical production ability (to hold or do something), poor (set of machines), weak research and extension institutions, and 
 the low prices of staple valuable things (Reardon et 
 al., 1997; Zeller et al., 1999). (not well developed) (away from cities) 
 credit markets also limit farming-based (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) 
 and working well growth that depends on the increased use of (bought) inputs (von Braun et al., 
