 2. Area description, survey way(s) of doing things and 
 adoption model 
 The study area in southern Cameroon was selected 
 based on (probably true) (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) of the growing importance of strengthened/got worse (plant-related) production in this area (Fig. 2). (away from cities) densities lie between 36 and 70 
 people per km2 although denser pockets more than 
 150 people are common (RGPH, 1993; Santoir, 
 1995). Population pressures are usually higher than 
 in most other areas of central Africa, yet lower than 
 in much of humid west Africa. The climax green plants 
 is semi-(dropping leaves every autumn) moist (related to areas near the Equator/hot and humid) forest. Mean once-a-year 
 rainfall ranges from 1350 to 1700 mm distributed in a 
 bimodal pattern which permits two rain-fed cropping 
 seasons: the first, from March to June and the second, 
 from August to November. 25% of (away from cities) families 
 also crop during the dry season from December to 
 February in inland valley bottoms using hand crop-watering/rinsing with water or water from hydro-morphic soils (IITA unpublished data). 
 Up until the spread of monocrop systems of (plant-related) production beginning in the 1970s, the three 
 cropping systems which ruled in the farming 
 
