 systems of the study area were the melon seed field, 
 the mixed food crop field and the cocoa agroforest. 
 The first two are once-a-year crop systems that are rotated 
 with a unplanted period in order to restore soil life-creating ability. 
 As (away from cities) (groups of people/animals/things) have grown, unplanted periods have 
 declined and differences in land holdings have become more drew attention to. For families with limited 
 land holdings, the melon seed field, which needs/demands 
 long unplanted periods of 10-15 years, has dropped out 
 of the farming system. The mixed food crop system 
 is managed by women and has remained an important 
 part of the farming system since pre-colonial times 
 (Guyer, 1984). This cropping system provides the 
 bulk of household food supply as well as marketed 
 (more than what's needed) of food crops. Most families helped grow 
 the field twice in the first and second rainy season 
 on different places/locations. With rare exception agro-chemicals 
 are not applied. (producing crops/helping something grow) of cocoa in small agroforests is an important money/money income source for about two-thirds of families in the area and accounts for about one-third of total money/money income 
 in these families (IITA unpublished household 
 data). 
 (plant-related) crops are marketed from (more than what's needed) coming from the mixed crop field and from (made to do one thing very well) 
 monocrop systems of (plant-related) production helped grow by men. The last thing just mentioned system is a (compared to other things) recent 
 
 197 
 
 incorporation, first described in the mid-1970s (Guyer, 
 1984). Discussions with village older (people) confirm this as 
 the period in which commercial (plant-related) production began to develop. An important (feature/ quality/ trait) of 
 the monocrop system is a high level of agro-chemical 
 use. 
 A randomised two-stage group-related sample of (away from cities) 
 families was done in July of 1997 to (ask lots of questions about/try to find the truth about) the importance of (plant-related) cash crops in 
 (away from cities) jobs. The study area was divided into 
 eight squares of 18 km Ã-- 18 km and groups (villages) 
 nearest the (land-area-based/location) centre of each square selected 
 from two layers: (i) those villages lying on all-weather 
 roads and (ii) those on seasonal roads as pointed to/showed 
 on 1:200,000 topographic maps. Within villages, the 
 survey team selected families randomly by choosing every nth household. The sampling period of time (or space) n was 
 equal to N/13, where N was the counted total number 
 of families in the village and 13 the desired sample size for each village. A local guide helped in the 
 list of families. In all, 16 villages were 
 sampled and a total of 208 families interviewed 
 using a structured list of questions given/gave in the 
 local Beti language. The list of questions gathered described/explained 
 production information on the two most important 
 commercial crops produced by the household. The 
 survey data were used to describe practices in 
 (the study of plants) production, and to model the adoption of 
 intensive monocrop systems. 
 The adoption of intensive monocrop production systems was modelled using the logit separate binary 
 moving backward model (Maddala, 1983; Amemiya, 1985). 
 The model assumes an hidden (under) hidden/covered up adoption changeable yia-- defined by the relationship: 
