 The model focus is on the (things that decide other things) of the adoption of intensive monocrop production systems. The 
 reduced form of the model is 
 ADOPT = Î±0 + Î²1 MEN + Î²2 WOMEN + Î²3 CHILD 
 + Î²4 AGE + Î²5 EDUC + Î²6 MELON 
 + Î²7 MFOOD + Î²8 COCOA + Î²9 WPROD 
 + Î²10 COSTKM, 
 where the (thing that changes (like a test score) because of something else that you control (like study time)) (ADOPT) equals one, 
 if the production system used by the household to 
 produce its most commercially important (plant-related) 
 crop was a monocrop, and otherwise equals zero. 
 The household gift of family labour is 
 expected to positively affect the chance of adoption, given the labour-intensive nature of commercial 
 (the study of plants) production and (compared to other things) undeveloped 
 local labour markets. Labour (numbers that change/things that change) in the model 
 include the number of adult males (MEN), adult females (WOMEN), and children under 16 years of 
 age (CHILD). The age of household heads (AGE) 
 and their educational accomplishment (EDUC) capture 
 differences in the quality of management. 
 Land gifts play an important role in the (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) process (Boserup, 1965; Binswanger and 
 McIntire, 1987). In southern Cameroon, the institution 
 of patrilineal (something valuable you get when older relatives die) with an equal division of land 
 holdings along with very limited land sales and fast 
 population growth has resulted in less the average land holding per farm household. Matching with 
 Boserup's population-driven view of technical change, 
 this should increase the chance of strengthened/got worse (plant-related) production. Correct measures of farm size 
 were hard to get through farmer interview, as 
 land had not been surveyed and local area measures 
 do not exist. To deal with this measurement issue, the 
 number of melon seed fields cropped in the last 12 
 months (MELON), was used as an instrumental (number or thing that changes). The 10-15 year unplanted needed thing for this field 
 
 hints that only families with large (areas of owned land) 
 can still maintain this system. To test whether intensive (the study of plants) is replacing (producing crops/helping something grow) of the usual mixed crop field, a count of the number of these 
 fields cropped in the last 12 months (MFOOD) was 
 included in the model. 
 Research in other places (Govereh and Jayne, 1999; 
 Strasberg et al., 1999) has written about cooperation between cash crop and food crop (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) due in 
 part to the help of liquidity restrictions when 
 credit markets are missing. To test the guess 
 that cocoa money/money income provide liquidity that increases 
 the chance of stronger moncrop (plant-related) 
 production, the level of cocoa production (COCOA) 
 in the 12 months before the interview was included. 
 Women's participation in the process of technical change is often held back by information gaps 
 and weakened access to productive useful things/valuable supplies (Bzugu 
 and Kwaghe, 1997; Orr, 2000). A dummy (number or thing that changes) (WPROD), pointing to/showing cases where the principal 
 decision-maker was a women, tests for (male/female status) differences in the participation in intensive monocrop 
 production. 
 The condition of (away from cities) roads and the amount of cars and trucks affect market access and search and information costs, which have been shown to influence 
 (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) processes (Odhiambo, 1998; Zang and 
 Fan, 2001). Although the 16 villages in the sample 
 are within 100 km of Yaounde, local differences in 
 road quality and the amount of cars and trucks can 
 be significant. The per kilometre cost of personal bush 
 taxi transport to Yaounde (COSTKM) provides an instrumental measure of these differences and is expected to worsens/decreases the chance of 
 adoption. 
 
 3. Results 
 All of the 208 families had marketed at least 
 one (plant-related) crop in the 12 months before the 
 interview. A amazing (many different kinds of people or things) of crops was marketed with the mean household selling nearly 18 
 different crops. Overall, families identified 34 different crops as among their principal (first and second 
 rank in importance) sources of (plant-related) money/money income. 
 Tomato, dessert bananas and green maize were referred to/were given a ticket 
 most often (Table 1). 
 
