 4. Discussion of results 
 The positive effects of the number of men (MEN) 
 and the number of children (CHILD) hints that 
 
 family labour is (ready for action) among adopters, although 
 the issue is not completely clear for child labour. If 
 the decision-maker views children's education as an 
 investment good, an increase in the number of children would increase the decision maker's demand 
 for his/her children's education which could provide an other choice to the labour demand guess 
 for the positive coefficient on CHILD. Further (act of asking questions and trying to find the truth about something) of intra-household money/money income distribution, 
 labour portion, and household expense must resolve this issue. The number of women 
 in the household (WOMEN) and the educational 
 accomplishment of the household head (EDUC) did not 
 influence the chance of adoption, although there 
 was a significantly greater educational accomplishment 
 (Student's t = 2.59, P = 0.01) among adopters 
 (Table 3). 
 When women were the principal agent in management decisions (WPROD), there was a lower chance of adoption. Women's wide range of responsibilities in village (community of people/all good people in the world) limits their ability (to hold or do something) for adopting 
 labour-intensive technology systems. In the few cases 
 where women were using monocrop systems they 
 were mainly producing traditional African leafy vegetables in the dry season when other labour demands 
 are reduced. 
 The negative effect of MELON, a (substitute-related) measure 
 of land availability, points to/shows that increasing land restrictions positively influence the adoption of commercial (plant-related) production systems. This suggests 
 that, ceteris paribus, efforts to (help increase/show in a good way) (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) 
 of (the study of plants) production should target areas of (compared to other things) high population pressure. 
 The number of survival/income-oriented mixed food 
 crop fields, MFOOD, did not influence the adoption 
 of monocrop (the study of plants). Production from this field 
 system remains an important household goal for 
 both adopters and non-adopters alike. Many adopting families have included the monocrop field on 
 the front end of the mixed food crop/fallow rotation 
 by that/in that way economising on labour for unplanted clearing 
 while maintaining the survival/income (thing that's given/work that's done) of the 
 mixed food crop field. The important cultural role attached to the (producing crops/helping something grow) of the mixed food crop field 
 by the women of southern Cameroon (Guyer, 1984) 
 and the limited access of most families to (away from cities) 
 food markets also add/give to its toughness among 
 adopting families. 
 
 J. Gockowski, M. NdoumbÂ´e / Farming-based Money flow 30 (2004) 195-202 
 
 The cash needed things for intensive (the study of plants) 
 production combined with the failure of formal (away from cities) 
 credit institutions present a restriction to adoption 
 especially for useful thing/valuable supply-poor families. (money-related) 
 demands of intensive production likely underlie the 
 positive effect of cocoa money/money income (COCOA) on adoption. Mean cocoa sales among adopters during the 
 survey were more than double those of non-adopters; 
 the injection of cocoa money/money income guessed at more 
 than 500 US$_$ into the household (process of people making, selling, and buying things) helped (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) into other businesses/projects. Almost the same  effects between coffee and intensive (the study of plants) have also been noted in the western area of 
 Cameroon (Temple and Fadani, 1997). This hints that past policies in Cameroon supporting small 
 holder tree crop production improved/increased 
 the adoption of strengthened/got worse commercial (the study of plants) 
 production, although the effect is (compared to other things) inelastic 
 (Table 5). 
 The age of the household head was negatively connected with the chance of adoption. Younger farmers were more likely to adopt and the effect of age 
 on the chance of adoption was elastic (Table 5) 
 suggesting that policies, which impact (information about people/combinations of different kinds of people) 
 and traveling patterns would also affect the chance of adoption. Macroeconomic events beginning in 
 the late 1980s may have slowed (away from cities)-city-based  traveling 
 and increased the group of young farmers in the (away from cities) 
 population (Gockowski and Ndoumbe, 1999). 
 The instrumental (number or thing that changes) for (away from cities) road (set of machines) and communications, COSTKM, also had significant and elastic effect on the chance of intensive 
 (the study of plants) production. Ability to stretch at the sample mean 
 (maximum) is a'1.12 (a'2.59), which highlights the 
 importance of public investments in (away from cities) transportation (set of machines) in the process of farming-based (process by which something becomes stronger or worse). 
 
 5. Ends/end results 
 (the study of plants) is providing a pathway for (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) among smallholders in southern Cameroon driven 
 by growth in city-based  what people want to buy and high relative 
 prices. Its use in the usual farming system 
 enables the money-saving use of soil changes that 
 provide a means for facing the pressing issue of 
 soil nutrient (everything is gone). 
 
 201 
 
 (changes in people) have played a big part in 
 the (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) of (plant-related) production. Fast 
 rates of urbanisation, which in Cameroon averaged 
 over 7% in the 1970s and 1980s, have resulted in big demand growth in the city-based  markets of West 
 and central Africa. A slowing of (away from cities)-to-city-based  traveling in the 1990s connected with macroeconomic 
 (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) changes/recalculations including the 1994 currency 
 (reduction of value) appears to have increased the group of 
 younger farmers in the study area. Younger farmers were much more likely to adopt intensive 
 monocrop systems. This is an example of the important second-order effects of (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) changes/recalculations that 
 often escape the written statement/attention of policy makers. 
 Marketing costs have a significant and elastic effect on the adoption of intensive (the study of plants) systems. 
 Greater public investment in (away from cities) roads and a downward (change to make better/related to changing something) of taxes/import taxes now going beyond 100% 
 on new transport vehicles would help lower marketing costs. The diffusion of information on input and 
 crop prices, and quality differentials for these (compared to other things) dangerous markets is another public helping action 
 which would lower market search costs and improve 
 market (wasting very little while working or producing something). Local language radio broadcasts are 
 among the most (producing a lot for a given amount of money) methods of information 
 provision (Robbins, 2000). 
 The combined influence of transport cost and increasing land (not enough of something) on the adoption of stronger 
 production systems suggests targeting development efforts in areas of higher population densities with better 
 road (set of machines). For central Africa, areas away from cities in 
 the edge/edges of city-based  centres are the most likely domains for (plant-related) (process by which something becomes stronger or worse), rather than the 
 country seen as poorly developed transport (set of machines) and thinly distributed (groups of people/animals/things). Appropriate domains in west Africa are likely to be larger than 
 in central Africa due to higher overall population densities and better (away from cities) (set of machines). 
 The cooperation between cocoa production and (the study of plants) (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) hints that promotion of 
 traditional export crops has added/has given to the (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) of farming-based systems in the study area. 
 Whether almost the same  processes of (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) and (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) have happened among the cocoa and 
 coffee producers of Cote d'Ivoire, Nigeria and Ghana 
 warrants further study. 
 Women producers were not participating in intensive monocrop production. Efforts to deal with this 
 
